How to train agents in two-player competitive MDPs? We propose \xe2\x80\x9cCompetitive Policy optimization (CoPO)\xe2\x80\x9d a fundamental policy gradient approach. The traditional methods (GDA) consider linear approximations of the game objectives to design policy updates and diverge in even simple cases. We propose to exploit the game-theoretic nature of the agents\xe2\x80\x99 interaction and explicitly deploy bilinear approximation of game objective. We instantiate CoPO in two ways:(i) competitive policy gradient and (ii) trust-region competitive policy optimization. We provide PG theorems for them, and empirically show that they ROCK!!. They are stable optimizers, converge to sophisticated strategies and score high. Paper: https://lnkd.in/dfdXznZ Code: https://lnkd.in/dBmhTvF For more cool videos, have a look at our CoPO site at https://lnkd.in/db8ZD_m This work is part of my Master's thesis at ETH Z\xc3\xbcrich. I am grateful to Prof. Anima Anandkumar for providing the opportunity to work with her at Caltech. Amortized time complexity often considers large inputs for worst case analysis. Oh! Ok! But, Why? Because it might happen that for smaller input sizes, an inefficient approach or algorithm might perform better than the efficient counterparts. Like Cocktail sort or Circle sort can match upto the famous Merge and Heap sorting algorithms for smaller inputs. Don't believe me? Need an example to visualize? There you go! Lessons: Always consider large input size (usually N), next time you are going for an interview. Abhishek Somani Source: Reddit. I'll try my best to speak on behalf of everyone who's just been admitted into this program. This is addressed to the mentors of GRIP: While we're all glad to have secured an internship (which is an amazing initiative for students during difficult times), there seems to be a bit of a communication barrier between us, the hired interns, and you, our mentors. Apart from the email that we received, there hasn't been any official validation of our acceptance - whether on Internshala or an offer letter. Moreover, quite a few people here haven't received tasks pertaining to the roles we've applied for (particularly Data Science & Machine Learning). While we're aware that the format of the internship is completely virtual and requires us to work independently, we feel a lack of connection to the work we've been assigned, because of the aforementioned issues. Since it's been clarified that the DS/ML related tasks will be delivered to us in a week's time, we'd like to ask you if there's any sort of official confirmation of our hiring - particularly through an offer letter (or a certificate of completion once the program is completed). Virender Sehwag was playing County cricket in England for Leicestershire against Middlesex. Abdul Razzaq was reverse swinging the ball violently making it difficult to play. Jeremy Snape was the other Batsman with Sehwag on that day. In between over change, Snape suggested to improvise technique to counter Razzaq's swing. Interestingly Sehwag identified that rather than bowler , the half shining ball is the actual problem. He said to Snape " The next over is of a spinner, let me try for a Six and I will make ball disappear out of stand." Sultan of Multan, then hits it for six as planned. The above story is very interesting if I look at it from entrepreneurial Journey and narrate it as; Founders Sehwag & Snape were facing a competition from Razzaq's innovation. Snape decided to share his thought process over it. S & S decide to find the root cause problem and develop a solution for the same. They found it from their analysis that, NOT the bowler but the half Shine of the ball is the problem. They act accordingly to make the ball disappear. What made S&S win is , the pin pointed pain point identification, team work, and execution. #cricket #entrepreneurship

I am following a lot of #placementcoordinator on this platform. I often read their posts and their efforts to get opportunities for the students amaze me. But one thing that always leaves me worried is the lack of focus on the most basic goal i.e. preparing the students for jobs. This ranges from skill development, CV making, interview practice to helping with placement hurdles like Case Study puzzles or aptitude tests. In 2016, I was placed in a Startup on Day 3. I went to meet the interviewer in person and he simply said the level of preparation is decreasing batch by batch. We are here talking about IITK and on day 3 more than 70% students are still looking for opportunities. In other words,70% students are not prepared enough for potential job. I started looking for a job after a few months of working there, which is common with 40-50% of freshers. I applied for analytics, financial firms, startups and I realised the value of IITK tag during the process - more or less nothing. All the companies asked me technical stuff or case studies, which were directly relevant to the job I was applying for. This isn't just my experience, it's the bitter truth. Start focussing on learning and improving your skills. Because campus placement is not the end, it's just the beginning.
Abhishek shared this
Does the data science interview work? We teach how to crack the data science interview. We don't often ask if we are doing the interview in useful ways. Here are 5 things ideas I'd use more: 1. Even if SQL isn\xe2\x80\x99t part of the position I want to know the conceptual ideas behind it are mastered. Data manipulation is and always will be key. 2. Heavier emphasis on design of experiment and practical statistical analysis. Less flashcard type answers and more in depth discussion of why and how to setup and analyze." 3. Make a presentation about your work or a major project and its impact a required part of an interview. It says more (to me at least) than reciting how random forest works. 4. Given a half hour to read another colleague\xe2\x80\x99s work, give feedback on it. Articulate what was done well and how you might approach it differently. 5. Give the candidate a chance to have a \xe2\x80\x9cchoice module\xe2\x80\x9d to show what they are best at. Sometimes interviews miss what makes someone extraordinary. What would you change/add/remove from the process? This is a tough question, so any insights are awesome! #datascience #machinelearning #analytics
